SSH https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/ssh-essentials-working-with-ssh-servers-clients-and-keys#ssh-overview

The most common way of connecting to a remote Linux server is through SSH. SSH stands for Secure Shell and provides a safe and secure way of executing commands, making changes, 
and configuring services remotely. When you connect through SSH, you log in using an account that exists on the remote server.


Commpnly used orders

## ðŸ”¹ **Basic SSH Commands**

| Command                        | Description                   | Example                                   |
| ------------------------------ | ----------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `ssh user@host`                | Connect to a remote server    | `ssh admin@203.0.113.25`                  |
| `ssh -p PORT user@host`        | Connect using a custom port   | `ssh -p 2222 admin@203.0.113.25`          |
| `ssh -i keyfile.pem user@host` | Connect with a private key    | `ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa admin@203.0.113.25` |
| `ssh user@host "command"`      | Run a single command remotely | `ssh admin@203.0.113.25 "uptime"`         |
| `exit`                         | Exit the SSH session          | `exit`                                    |

---

## ðŸ”¹ **File Transfer (without SFTP)**

| Command                            | Description                 | Example                                           |
| ---------------------------------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
| `scp file user@host:/path`         | Upload file to remote       | `scp index.html admin@203.0.113.25:/var/www/html` |
| `scp user@host:/path/file .`       | Download file from remote   | `scp admin@203.0.113.25:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf .`  |
| `scp -r folder user@host:/path`    | Upload folder recursively   | `scp -r project admin@203.0.113.25:/opt/`         |
| `scp -r user@host:/path folder`    | Download folder recursively | `scp -r admin@203.0.113.25:/var/log logs`         |
| `scp -P PORT file user@host:/path` | Use custom port             | `scp -P 2222 file.txt admin@203.0.113.25:/tmp`    |

---

## ðŸ”¹ **SSH Session Management**

| Command                 | Description                                      | Example                          |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------- |
| `ssh-copy-id user@host` | Copy public key to remote for passwordless login | `ssh-copy-id admin@203.0.113.25` |
| `ssh-add keyfile`       | Add a key to SSH agent                           | `ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_rsa`          |
| `ssh-agent bash`        | Start a new agent session                        | `ssh-agent bash`                 |
| `Ctrl + D`              | Close the SSH connection                         | *(press Ctrl+D)*                 |

---

## ðŸ”¹ **Useful Options**

| Option                                  | Description                                      |
| --------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| `-v`                                    | Verbose mode (debug connection issues)           |
| `-C`                                    | Enable compression for faster transfer           |
| `-t`                                    | Force pseudo-terminal (for interactive commands) |
| `-L local_port:remote_host:remote_port` | Local port forwarding                            |
| `-R remote_port:local_host:local_port`  | Remote port forwarding                           |
| `-D port`                               | Dynamic SOCKS proxy                              |

---

## ðŸ“Œ **Example Workflows**

**1. Connect and run a command:**

```bash
ssh admin@203.0.113.25 "df -h"
```

**2. Copy a backup to local machine:**

```bash
scp admin@203.0.113.25:/var/backups/db.sql.gz ~/backups/
```

**3. Upload code to server:**

```bash
scp -r ./myapp admin@203.0.113.25:/var/www/
```


